<div class="solution-section">
<h4>Solutions</h4>

<ol>
<li>We take mod 10 and simplify. This becomes $k=2^8+8^2 \pmod{10}$. From our digit cycle of 2, we can find that $k = 6+4=0 \pmod{10}$. Thus, $k^2 = 0 \pmod{10}$. Since $k=0 \pmod{4}$ (why?), $2^k = 2^4 = 6 \pmod{10}$. If we add these two, the units digit is $\boxed{6}$.</li>
<li>$\boxed{\text{(Exercise for reader)}}$</li>
<li>Check the digit cycle of 7, which has length 4 (like the cycle of 2). Conduct the same approach as we did before, and find that it will result in $7^1 = \boxed{7}$.</li>
</ol>
</div>

<p>An infinite number of problems can be created and solved in this manner.</p>

<h2>CRT</h2>
<p>CRT primarily deals with solving systems with multiple congruences. The reason behind this is that it says if $x=y \mod{mn}$, $x=y \mod{m}$ and $x=y \mod{n}$. This is useful because it allows us to split up a modular congruence into smaller pieces. In practical applications, we can find a system of modular congruences which can be combined into one larger equation.</p>
<p>CRT also gives us the solution to two modular congruences easily as</p>
\begin{align*} &n \equiv r_1 \pmod{m_1}, \quad n \equiv r_2 \pmod{m_2}, \quad (m_1, m_2) = 1 \\ &\text{Find } k_1 \text{ and } k_2 \text{ such that } k_1 m_1 \equiv 1 \pmod{m_2}, \quad k_2 m_2 \equiv 1 \pmod{m_1} \\ &\text{Then } n \equiv k_2 m_2 r_1 + k_1 m_1 r_2 \pmod{m_1 m_2} \end{align*}
<p>For example, we may encounter the problem of finding the last two digits of a number (usually exponentiated). In this case, we would like to take the number mod 100. However, since 100 is such a large modulus, we are unlikely to find enough information to directly solve the equation. However, if we take it mod 4 and mod 25, it can be combined into mod 100. For example, if we have that $n = 0 \mod{4}, 12 \mod{25}$, using our formula we can easily find n = $19*4*12 +1*25*0=-288=12 \mod{100}$, or by solving the congruence equation $n = 25x+12$ and substituting $25x+12 = 0 \mod{4}$, we can get $x = 0 \mod{4}$. This is equivalent to x =4j, and substituting we get $n=100j+12$. This implies that n mod 100 is 12.</p>

<div class="exercise-section">
<h4>Exercises</h4>

<ol>
<li>What are the last two digits of $7^{222}$?</li>
</ol>
</div>
<div class="solution-section">
<h4>Solutions</h4>

<ol>
<li>We use mod $4$ and $25$ to decompose the last 2 digits which would be mod $100$. First, $7 \equiv -1 \pmod{4}$ so $7^{222} \equiv (-1)^{222} \equiv 1 \pmod{4}$, and $7^2=49 \equiv -1 \pmod{25}$ so $7^{222}=(7^2)^{111} \equiv (-1)^{111} \equiv -1 \equiv 24 \pmod{25}$. Thus we have $n \equiv 1 \pmod{4}, \; n \equiv 24 \pmod{25}$. Writing $n=25x+24$ and substituting gives $25x+24 \equiv 1 \pmod{4} \Rightarrow x \equiv 1 \pmod{4} \Rightarrow x=4j+1$, so $n=25(4j+1)+24=100j+49$. This implies $n \equiv 49 \pmod{100}$, so the last two digits are $\boxed{49}$.</li>
</ol>
</div>




<h2>Fermat's Little Theorem</h2>
<p>Fermat’s little theorem says that for any prime $p$ and any integer $a$, $a^p - a$ is a multiple of $p$. Alternatively, $a^p \equiv a \pmod{p}$. If $a$ and $p$ are coprime, this implies that $a^{p-1} \equiv 1 \pmod{p}$. Fermat’s theorem is particularly useful in simplifying large modular congruences. For example, we can use Fermat’s theorem to simplify $7^{2017} \pmod{11}$. First, we apply Fermat’s theorem in the form with one. This means that $7^{10} \equiv 1 \pmod{11}$. Then, if we exponentiate each side, any multiple of $10$ is also congruent to $1$. Thus, $7^{2017} \equiv 7^7 \pmod{11}$. From here, set $7 \equiv -4 \pmod{11}$, yielding $(-4)^7 \pmod{11}$, which can be computed to $(-4)^7 \equiv 6 \pmod{11}$.</p>

<p>It is an effective exercise to set any arbitrary power modulo any prime and evaluate. Wolfram Alpha can calculate the result to check your work.</p>

<p>For example:</p>
<p>$3^{31} \pmod{7}, \quad 29^{25} \pmod{11}, \quad 128^{129} \pmod{17}$</p>

<p>Working $29^{25} \pmod{11}$ simplifies to $(-4)^{25} \pmod{11}$, and since $(-4)^{10} \equiv 1 \pmod{11}$, we have $(-4)^5 \equiv -1024 \equiv -1 \pmod{11}$.</p>
<h2>Totient Function + Extension to Fermat’s</h2>
<p>Euler’s totient function is defined as the number of coprime numbers to a number n. This function is usually denoted as phi or $\Phi (n)$. For low values of n, we can directly compute. For example, $\Phi (9) = 6$ since 3, 6, and 9 are coprime to 9. We note particularly that for n is a prime, the phi function returns n-1; since the only non coprime number to n is itself. For higher values of n, we resort to Euler’s product formula. In particular, the value is n times (1-1/p), where p is every prime factor of n. We can use this to extend Fermat’s little theorem such that $a^{\Phi(n)-1}=1 \mod{n}$ even when n is not prime.</p>
<p>If $1 \le n \le 1000$, what value of n minimizes $\Phi {n}/n$?</p>
<p>Use the formula of the phi function. Then this simplifies to (1-1/p) for all prime factors of n. To minimize this, we note that each term is minimized when p is as small as possible. Thus, when p is 2, it is the minimum for one prime factor. But if there are more factors, we want to extend it as far as possible. This means $n$ is $k!$, and $n \le 1000$ means n is 720 or 6!.</p>
<h2>Wilson’s Theorem</h2>
<p>Wilson’s theorem consists of a bidirectional statement. $(p-1)!=-1 \mod{p}$ if and only if p is a prime number. The proof of this theorem is vastly beyond the scope of elementary number theory. In practice, Wilson’s theorem is most effective when dealing with factorials in modular congruences. It can be used both to simplify factorials as well as to prove a number to be prime. For example, take 30! Mod 899. By factoring the difference of perfect squares, we get factors of 29 and 31. Since both are prime, we want to use CRT to combine the linear congruence. Firstly, 30! Is obviously divisible by 29. Then, using Wilson’s theorem, $(31-1)! =-1 \mod{31}$ which can then be combined to be 464 mod 899.</p>

