<ol>
<li>$\boxed{\text{All primes p satisfy this}}$ since $(p-2)! \equiv (p-1)(p-2)(p-3)! \equiv (-1)(-2)(p-3)! \equiv 2(p-3)! \equiv -1 \pmod{p}$.</li>
<li>Recall $(p-1)! \equiv -1\pmod{p}$, then we can see trivially that $(p-1)! \equiv (p-1)(p-2)(p-3)!$ So after applying the modulo $p$ we yield this result: $(p-1)! \equiv (-1)(-2)(p-3)! \pmod{p}$, so with using wilson's we get $2(p-3)! \equiv -1 \pmod{p}$, sub this back into the initial condition, yielding $2 \cdot 2 \equiv -1 \pmod{p} \rightarrow 4 \equiv -1 \pmod{p}$, thus trivially notice $\boxed{p=5}$ is the only prime that works.</li>
</ol>
