<h2>Diophantine Equations</h2>
<p>Diophantine equations are generally equations of form ax+by=c. We seek integer solutions for x, y. Firstly, we must confirm that c is divisible by the gcd(a,b)=d (why?). Once one solution is found, all solutions are of form $(x_0+ k\frac{b}{d}, y_0-k\frac{a}{d}. The easiest way to find solutions in complicated equations is the Euclidian algorithm, but inspection can often work as well. For example, take 2x+3y=5. By inspection, x=y=1 is easy to find. Since 2 and 3 are coprime, d = 1. Then, the solutions are formed (1+3k,1-2k). Trying some other solutions (4,-1) should convince us of the truth.</p>
