<h2>Lifting the Exponent Lemma</h2>
<p>Before the lemma is introduced, we must create some definitions. First, we will consider prime factorization. It is commonly known that any whole number $n$ can be expressed as</p>
$
j = p_1^{k_1} \cdot p_2^{k_2} \cdot  p_3^{k_3}\cdot  \dots \cdot  p_n^{k_n}
$
<p>where the sequence $p_n$ is the prime factors of $n$, and the sequence $k_n$ the powers of the prime factors. When we work with prime factorization, we have divisibility rules and the modulus system to be able to determine the sequence $p_n$, but for this lemma we will work with $k_n$. With this in mind, we will define a new function $v_p(j)$ such that the following statements are equivalent.</p>
$
v_{p_n}(j) = k_n \iff p^k | j\text{ and } p^{k+1} \nmid j
$
<p>Please note that $p_n$ denotes a prime number. If we look at what this definition means, we can see that it is simply the value of the exponent of the prime $p_n$. To break this down more exactly, we can see that the right side of the bidirectional arrow really just says that $k_n$ is the largest number that still makes $p^k$ divide n. As an example, if we consider $24$, we can see that $p_2(24) = 3$, and also that $p_3(24)=1$. This is obvious because $8$ divides $24$, but $16$ does not divide $24$. Similarly, $3$ divides $24$, but $9$ does not. Now with this down, we can move onto the actual lemma.</p>
<p>Now, more generally. Let $p$ be a prime, $x$ and $y$ integers, $n$ a positive integer, and suppose that $p |x-y $ but that $p\nmid x$ and $p\nmid y$. Then if p is not $2$,</p>
$
v_p(x^n-y^n) = v_p(x-y)+v_p(n)
$
<p>If p is $2$ and $n$ is even, then:</p>
$
v_2(x^n-y^n) = v_2(x-y) + v_2(n)+v_2(x+y)-1
$
<p>If $n$ is odd, v_2(x^n-y^n) = v_2(x-y)</p>
<p>We can also provide a useful extension. If $n$ is an odd integer, then we can substitute $y = -y$ to obtain:</p>
$
v_p(x^n+y^n) = v_p(x+y)+v_p(n)
$
<p>These four provide the general basis to work with all primes, and now we proceed with a proof.</p>
<p>We take the case where $p$ is odd, with the understanding that when $p=2$ the proof is similar. Firstly, we will seek to prove the following:</p>
$
v_p(x^p-y^p)=v_p(x-y)+1
$
<p>Although this seems very abstract, we will inevitably use induction to solve this. We will factor out $x-y$.</p>
$
x^p-y^p = (x-y)(x^{p-1}+yx^{p-2}+y^2x^{p-3} +\dots +xy^{p-2}+y^{p-1})
$
<p>Now we will apply our function $v_p$ on the above equation. Note specifically that similar to the Law Of Exponents (you add the exponents with the same base), multiplication of $(x-y)$ of the right part when taken under the function $v_p$ is converted to the sum of both parts under the function. Now we are halfway there, and we only need to find that the right term of the equation is equal to one to satisfy the initial claim.</p>
$
v_p(x^p-y^p)=v_p(x-y)+v_p(x^{p-1}+yx^{p-2}+y^2x^{p-3} +\dots +xy^{p-2}+y^{p-1})
$
<p>In order to find this right hand side equal to 1, we will use the definition of $v_p$, namely that it is divisible by $p$ and not $p^2$. This is because to get $v_p(j) = 1$, $p |j$ and $p^2 \nmid j$.</p>
<p>To remove $y$, we use the condition $p|x-y$, which can be rearranged in modulus terms as $x-y = 0 \pmod{p}$ or $x \equiv y \pmod{p}$ which further can be written to say $y = x+pk$ for some integer $k$.  To substitute each individual term we will denote $n$ as the $n$th term of the sequence, taking modulus $p^2$ to remove terms that will not change our stated goal above. Then,</p>
$
x^{p-1}y^n= x^{p-1-n}(x+kp)^n = x^{p-1-n}(x^n+n(kp)x^{n-1}+\frac{n(n-1)}{2}(kp)^2x^{n-2} \dots)
$
$
= x^{p-1}+ n(kp)x^{p-2} \pmod{p^2}
$
<p>This can now be applied to our other equation, giving:</p>
$
x^{p-1}+yx^{p-2}+y^2x^{p-3} +\dots +xy^{p-2}+y^{p-1} =
$
$
x^{p-1} + (x^{p-1} + kpx^{p-2})+(x^{p-1} + 2kpx^{p-2})+ \dots + (x^{p-1} + (p-2)kpx^{p-2})+(x^{p-1} + (p-1)kpx^{p-2}) =
$
$
px^{p-1}+(1+2+3+\dots+p-2+p-1)kpx^{p-2} = px^{p-1}+\frac{p(p-1)}{2}kpx^{p-2} =
$
$
px^{p-1} \pmod{p^2}
$
<p>From here, it is clear that our polynomial is divisible by $p$ and not $p^2$, which proves our initial claim. Lets restate the original problem and continue.</p>
$
v_p(x^n-y^n) = v_p(x-y)+v_p(n)
$
<p>Define $n$ as $p^ab$, where $p, b$ are coprime. We can write:</p>
<p>$v_p(x^n - y^n)$</p>
<p>$v_p\!\big((x^{p^k})^a - (y^{p^k})^a\big)$</p>
<p>$v_p(x^{p^k} - y^{p^k})$</p>
<p>$v_p\!\big((x^{p^{k-1}})^p - (y^{p^{k-1}})^p\big)$</p>

<p>Which applying our proved statement will follow naturally:</p>
$
=v_p(x^{p^{k-1}}-y^{p^{k-1}})+1
$
<p>Eventually, by repeating that process we will eventually now obtain</p>
$
v_p(x-y)+k = v_p(x-y)+v_p(n)
$
<p>This lemma does show up often on competition math sets. For example, in 2022 this problem showed up. Most people solved alternatively, but the LTE Lemma makes this problem trivial.</p>

<div class="exercise-section">
<h4>Exercises</h4>

<ol>
<li>Problem 17, AMC 10B 2022: One of the following numbers is not divisible by any prime number less than $10.$ Which is it? (A) $2^{606}-1$ (B) $2^{606}+1$ (C) $2^{607}-1$ (D) $2^{607}+1$ (E) $2^{607}+3^{607}$</li>
</ol>
</div>
<div class="solution-section">
<h4>Solutions</h4>

<ol>
<li> Proceed down each answer choice and apply LTE Lemma to each. For (A) $v_p(2^{606}-1) = v_p(2-1) +v_p(606)$. Clearly, we can see that when $p=3$, $v_p = 1$ which implies that (A) is divisible by $3$. For (B). We firstly note that we cannot apply the addition form of the LTE Lemma in this state, since 606 is not odd. Conveniently, we can write it like this. $v_p(2^{606}+1) = v_p(4^{303}+1) = v_p(4+1) + v_p(303)$. By squaring the $2$, we eliminate the even number and can see easily that (B) is divisible by 5. For (D), we can directly apply the lemma. $v_p(2^{607}+1) = v_p(2+1) + v_p(607)$ which means (D) is divisible by 3. Finally, (E). $v_p(2^{607}+3^{607}) = v_p(2+3) +v_p(607)$ which clearly denotes divisibility by 5. By elimination, we find the answer is $\boxed{C}$. For reference, we can also show this by using the lemma on C. $v_p(2^{607}-1) = v_p(2-1) +v_p(607)$ which since 1 and 607 are not divisible by a prime number, no prime divides C.</li>
</ol>
